  "content": [
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Classification Type based on Core access"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Service APIs can be Categorized into two types based on core access"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "Service API required by multiple cores for triggering and reading /writing of data",
        "Service API which are required by one partition only (e.g., initialization, shutdown)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Classification Type based on functionality"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Service APIs are categorized into below types based on its functionality"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "Trigger a control flow from service API to kernel API (if required including data)",
        "Read of a symbol from a global buffer",
        "Write a symbol to a global buffer, which is later-on polled by the kernel"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Classification Type based on functionality - Second Type"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "APIs can be classified as below types based on its functionality as"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "User API – The APIs which are accessible by users (like CDD, IoHwAb) to  trigger a control or to Read/write data",
        "Control APIs – Local core Scope APIs like Init, Deinit",
        "Kernel APIs – typically implemented in MCAL module where on calling USER API will call an Kernel API in local core"
      ]
    },
